<br>
Standing slowly, stretching muscles not used to sitting in one place so long, she begins to gather the aethers, tearing open a small hole in the fabric that is the world, and, stepping into it, she appears in the doorway of the Arena.  Casting a glance upward at the now open door, still awed by the scale of things, Mizzery walks into the arena, not hesitantly, but respectfully, her shrouded boots making little noise on the still blood-stained soil, packed down by the passing of so many people over the ages.<br>
<br>
Not far from the door lies the body of Gore, perhaps the strongest warrior ever of his kind, the armor clad form lying motionless now, dead and lifeless.  Crossing silently over to it, Mizzery looks down at the corpse, and, even after its owner's crimes against her and her love, she can't help but feel a sense of awe, and even a small bit of admiration.  What courage it must have taken for him to send his only remaining allies away after Xadria left him to die - to stand, one man, against more than a hundred.  How appropriate it is that he died here, she thinks, the Arena - a servant of War claiming a shrine to War as his tomb, a place where his service would be immortalized by the battles of generations to come.  Mad though he might have been, surely no warrior could have hoped for a better death, one against an army the likes of which Norrath had never seen.<br>
<br>
Looking up, Mizzery turns and leaves, padding away on quiet feet, careful not to disturb the dead.  She stops at the door though, her small figure framed by the massive stone-work on either side of her, the moon's silver light gently highlighting her features.  Once again surveying the now empty Arena, she pauses to think, how peaceful the place is now, the armies gone, the bodies of the dead long since picked over and carted away ... how ironically, almost paradoxically, and, certainly inappropriately, peaceful.<br>
<br>
... Still, for those of Norrath, death seems to be but a temporal thing, and she doubts the world has seen the last of Gore.<br>
